{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d88522e3-470e-46f9-8437-e85e44b200d4","content":"The page-level safe area setting controls the page's padding, but the **parent layout** of your Image also needs to opt out. Set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the layout containing your image:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n               Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nKey points:\n- **`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** on the `Grid` (or whatever layout wraps your Image) is what actually extends content behind system bars.\n- **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`** disables iOS safe area insets at the page level.\n- If you're using Shell, also add `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` on the page to hide the navigation bar.\n- On Android (API 35+ / .NET 9+), edge-to-edge is the default, but `IgnoreSafeArea` still controls whether your layout respects the insets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a80d9611-a5bf-4236-91f6-4adcc5225157","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what they might be missing:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Set `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` if using Shell navigation\n2. On Android, you need to opt into edge-to-edge display\n\n\n3. The key property is `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view itself—`SafeAreaEdges` on the ContentPage controls which edges the page respects, but individual views might still honor safe area insets. Let me reconsider what's actually needed for .NET 10 specifically, since there were changes to safe area handling in recent versions.\n\nFor .NET MAUI, the approach differs by platform: on iOS, I need to use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` or set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on layouts to extend into the safe area, while on Android 15+ with .NET 9+, apps are edge-to-edge by default but still require handling window insets properly. -specific to ignore safe area on iOS\n\nFor the page level in .NET MAUI, I believe the approach is:\n- Set the page to not use safe area (iOS-specific)\n- On Android, ensure edge-to-edge mode is enabled\n\nBut the user mentioned `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` - this might be a property I'm not fully recalling. Let me think...\n\nActually, in .NET MAUI there might not be a `SafeAreaEdges` property on ContentPage in the standard API. The user might be confusing it with something else, or it might be a newer .NET 10 API.\n\nThe most common solution for edge-to-edge in .NET MAUI is using `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on Layout types like Grid or StackLayout, and on iOS specifically applying `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to disable safe area constraints. For Android, edge-to-edge mode should be enabled by default in newer versions, and if using Shell navigation, I'd hide the nav bar with `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"`. The key insight is that the Image control or its parent layout needs `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` to actually extend to the edges, since page-level settings alone won't make the content itself ignore the safe area. feArea=\"True\"` on that layout.\n\nActually, I need to be more careful here about what's accurate for .NET 10 MAUI. The correct approach for edge-to-edge rendering is to set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the parent layout containing the image—this is the step most people miss, since page-level safe area settings don't automatically cascade down to child layouts.","outputTokens":1482,"requestId":"0819:3D4AC3:AB88F8:C69864:69F2AAC2"},"id":"aa49ff3c-a968-46